      <node TEXT="For such purposes  Artificial Intelligence  AI   namely Machine Learning   ML   has made a significant contribution during the COVID 19  pandemic  7 . Izquierdo et al. found that the  most common clinical characteristics determining admission to ICU  were fever  age  and tachypnea with without respiratory crackles  17 . This pandemic increased the research community  s  interest in finding practical solutions to mitigate the effects of this  problem  such as prediction models for ICU admissions  length of stay in  ICU  and discharge date. A semi parametric model  to probabilistically predict the LoS of COVID 19 patients in ICU was  applied. Researchers are often interested in improving prediction scenarios  that influence public decision guidance. Moreover  LoS in the ICU is  affected by abnormal values of many factors  namely lymphocyte ab  solute value  erythrocyte count  total cholesterol  adenovirus IgM anti  body  hypersensitive C reactive protein  high sensitivity troponin I  and  Q fever Rickettsia IgM antibody  23 . They  found also that age  weight  gender  and career are not affecting the  length of hospital stay." />
      <node TEXT="Also  these algorithms have been applied for many prediction pur  poses in the medical field such as breast cancer  diabetes  and other  diseases. They stated that the best predic   tion accuracy was achieved by using RF. The propsed models in this work were implemented using Python  programming language which provides several tools for machine  learning tasks. The trees protect each  other from their flaws  which explains why they have such a strong ef  fect. Gradient boosting is a technique that  can be utilized for both regression and classification tasks  33 . It is only appropriate to employ this  approach if the output of multiple classifiers disagrees. As a result   approaches for creating ensembles revolve around producing classifiers  that disagree with their predictions  39 ." />
      <node TEXT="To solve this imbalanced dataset issue  Syn  thetic Minority Oversampling Technique  SMOTE  was used. Because the dataset  is imbalanced  we could not depend on one performance measure. Algorithm Strength Weakness  Random Forest   RF    Collection of decision trees  that fit the data and cause  high variation in  classification    Data classification is based  on the most votes. Very sensitive to training  data which makes it error   prone. Up sampling of similar data  does not show any impact in  improving results  42 . Extreme  Gradient  Boosting   XGBoost    Designed to be used with  large complex datasets and  avoid model overfitting. The ensemble method  combines multiple weak  classifiers as a strong  classifier." />
      <node TEXT="For all developed models  feature selection did not contribute to  improving performance. Model 1 results were also compared to the other works in the liter  ature presented in  10 20 24  where different datasets were used with  ML prediction models. The obtained correlation results show that age  C Reactive  Protein  nasal oxygen support days  organ dysfunction or failure  LDH   blood oxygen saturation  headache  autoimmune disease  D dimer  and  ferritin are the features that can strongly indicate the need for patients to  be in ICU. These obtained results are aligned generally with the iden  tified features relevant to ICU admission in the literature which was  presented earlier in Table 2. Four prediction  models were developed using ML classifiers  RF  GB  XGBoost  and  Ensemble as those four classifiers are known to perform well for the  targeted purpose. K fold Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score  3 91.41  91.49  91.41  91.42   5 91.21  91.10  91.21  91.10   7 87.02  87.07  87.02  86.97   10 83.56  83.67  83.56  83.49   15 82.69  83.27  82.69  82.89    Table 10  The result of predicting the number of days to discharge from ICU class for  Model 3 with feature selection. K fold Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score  3 93.13  93.42  93.13  93.19   5 92.58  92.56  92.58  92.54   7 88.94  89.55  88.94  88.96   10 91.10  91.39  91.10  91.20   15 85.01  85.44  85.01  85.12    Table 12  The result of predicting the number of days to discharge from ICU class for  Model 4 with feature selection." />
      <node TEXT="The obtained results with this model are shown in Table 11  which achieved 93.13  accuracy without feature selection. For this purpose  four  prediction models were implemented using different ML classifiers with  multiple tuning of the parameters. Results  were compared in order to identify the highest performance model. 3 also shows the obtained accuracy of each model before and  after feature selection. It can be seen that RF provides the  best result in all performance measures as it scored 94.16   94.14    94.16   and 94.14  for accuracy  precision  recall  and F score Table 4  Entropy values for features included in the study. Attribute Entropy Evaluation  Gender 0.64  Age 4.03  DM 0.71  HTN 0.68  Cardiac 0.40  Obesity 0.31  Smoking 0.2  Vitamin D def  0.04  Renal 0.23  Liver disease 0.12  Autoimmune disease 0.10  Fever 0.71  Dry Cough 0.71  Fatigue 0.45  Headache 0.35  Dyspnea 0.64  Flu Symptoms 0.36  diarrhea 0.53  RR 2.86  Blood oxygen saturation  SATS  3.28  Mode of infection 0.80  1st sample 0.08  Chloroquine  Hydroxychloroquine 0.72  Azithromycin  Antibiotics 0.43  Steroids 0.63  Tocilizumab 0.56  Respiratory failure 0.17  Acute renal failure 0.10  Acute coronary syndrome 0.06  ARDS 0.06  GI complication 0.03  Nosocomial infection 0.03  Septic shock 0.06  Organ dysfunction or failure 0.13  lymph 5.35  Neut 5.56  LDH 5.64  ALT 4.34  AST 4.57  Trop 4.73  ferritin 5.93  D dimer 5.47  CRP 5.90   Table 5  The results of predicting the number of days to discharge from ICU class for  Model 1. K fold Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score  3 94.16  94.14  94.16  94.14   5 93.55  93.51  93.55  93.53   7 87.23  87.23  87.23  87.20   10 86.07  86.11  86.07  85.96   15 92.38  92.31  92.38  92.33    Table 6  The results of predicting the number of days to discharge from ICU class for  Model 1 with feature selection." />
